The Wall

thyra L.

The Wall

It was a sad and haunting place, both at the same time. From the first moment I entered the manor, I could not shake the hollowness that crept within me. It terrified me. It was also inviting me to seek further.


The manor was huge, three storey tall. although it was grand, it was also dull as it has been over half a century since someone has lived in it. Rumors in this town say that there are things inside that must remain unbothered for they cause great trouble once disturbed.


Inside the house, everything is draped in dusty white fabric. The chill ran through me as I stepped inside. The wooden floor boards creak when stepped on. It was overall dark but thanks to the huge windows on all the walls, there is still enough light to illuminate the inside of the house.

The Wall

I cannot help but be fascinated with everything I see in this property. everything was dark toned. From top to bottom, I can tell, the previous owners had impeccable taste. The chandeliers, all though not working, are all marvelous pieces of art by their own rights as each curve of the metal that props the light upright resembles the curves of vines found in the wilderness. The wallpaper, all though worn and old, still holds a glamour only the finest of its kind could ever hold. The all-wood furniture, all though dusty, is evidently finely finished and would once again shine once given a proper finish. And of course the grand staircase, oh the grandeurỊ I could already picture myself walking down those stairs in elegant gowns as everyone stare at me in admiration. This house is perfect for me, indeed.

The Wall

As I explored the manor more, I can’t help but remember the rumors I have hear on my way here. The locals said that buying this property was a huge mistake, they said I was ought to regret it once I find out the whole truth of its history. I never cared much for history. I like things for what they are now rather than what they have been before or what they might be tomorrow. For me, the now is the most important state to be in, so I live in the now. Never mind the past, it is over and will not be changed. Don’t worry about the future, it will come and you cannot stop it.


As I reached the second floor, I am more convinced that purchasing the house was a great investment. This level was full of antiques, mirrors, vases, stones, furniture, paintings, pictures and so much more. All of these have been hidden here, perfectly preserved as if the past fifty years had not happened. If it weren’t for the dust that piles on and on, I would have been sure that this manor is occupied by perhaps a rich old couple.

The Wall

I continued onto the next floor where the bedrooms are. One by one, I entered each room only to find them empty save for a bed and a lamp on top of a table. In the middle of this level, there is a fireplace. Perfect for this cold that is slowly gnawing at my bones. Beside it is a pile of firewood, also half a century years old by the looks of it. I propped the wood against each other to make a triangle and lit a fire using the matches I found on a drawer of the center table.


The flame started small but as I blew breath into it, it got big enough to warmed me. I sat in front of the fire until it warmed me enough to continue on my adventure.


I reached the master’s bedroom, at the end of the hall in the middle of the right and left wings of the house. From the size of the door, I can already guess how big a room it would be. It would be my room once I move in. I hope it has a big closet for all my clothes and shoes. For sure it does, it is big enough to have a big closet.

The Wall

I pushed the door open with a creaking sound. seems like the hinges need oil. I mentally noted that as I grazed over my soon-to-be bedroom with a smile of satisfaction. It was perfectỊ A king size canopy bed on the left side with the posts engraved with vines similar to the vines of the chandeliers. On each side of the bed are two side tables with black vintage lamps. On the foot of the bed is a wooden chest. The opposite wall to the door is almost wholly tainted glass. It was decorated with images of baby angels and crosses. The old owners must have been very religious.


On the right side of the room is a huge painting of The Last supper on the wall. Below it is a mismatched wall of bricks, not really blending in with the rest of the wall which was coves in dark green wallpaper with plants and vines design. My brows furrowed at the sight. On the left of the brick part is a vanity table, still with vintage make-up which probably belonged to the old lady of the house. On the other side is a shelf full of books save for the top row which had only one book with black cover.

The Wall

I love books. Even as a little girl, I have always loved books. I went closer to the shelf and picked up the black book. I then went to the dusty bed, patted a part of it clean and sat, fixing my skirt before I do so. I noticed the book had to writings on its cover, it was just plain pitch black. I opened it to the first page to find a name written in thin slanted letters at the bottom of the otherwise blank page-- Marie Elodie Moreau. I traced the ink with my finger and whispered the name. suddenly, the cold was back. I instinctively looked around the room to find an open window but of course found none. Then, I flipped another page.


March 17, 1956


The Spanish ships have just arrived. Although I was not permitted by my dear husband, I could not shake my curiosity of these foreign people. With the help of my maid, I managed to escape the estate for a while and have a glimpse of the Spaniard troops. They are strange in my eyes, with their brown skin sharp bone structures.

The Wall

However, one particular troop caught my eye. He was not like the rest of them, ugly. He was actually beautiful. The way the sun hit his eyes as it sunk below the horizon struck something within me that I cannot describe, and it changed me.


Am I committing a sin? A transgresion against my spouse? I do not know, my dear diary. And I also do not know what I felt when I looked into Senior Alejandro’s eyes earlier today. It felt good, but it cannot be good, surely. For I am married and am not free for courtship. May God help me.


I took a deep breath as I finished reading the writings of Madam Marie on that day. Despite of now knowing that this book is a diary, I already started reading it and I cannot stop myself from reading more of it. I released the breath I took and flipped more of the pages.

The Wall

March 31, 1956


Earlier this morning, Senior Alejandro and I went out for coffee at Cafe du Matin. Their white coffee there is splendid and I must say, the talk with the senior was lovely as well. He had this shimmer in his eyes whenever it was hit by light. There is sweetness in his lips and in the way he talks. It felt like everything he did was a show meant just for me and me only. I could watch him all day talk about his hobbies and interests. Alas, I could not do that! For at night, I must go home to my husband. God did not help me at all, no he did not. For he let me fall for another whilst being married. I wish you could help me, book you are nothing more than just pieces of paper bound into a book. I must face this dilemma on my own and do it fast. The more I wait, the worse it will get. That is all for now. Thank you for being here.

The Wall

April 3, 1956


I brought Alejandro in my room today. We had a wonderful time. I was so nervous the entire time that my husband will learn of him and I but thankfully, it went well.

I would tell you more but I am very much too tired. Ciao. April 6, 1956

Alejandro is here with me almost every day now. With my husband almost always away for business, he could stay the night. I like that. We have more time with each other like that. He even gave me his necklace, a metal Gothic cross. I wear it all the time now and I think it suits me, he also told me that it did. Until next time, dear.

The Wall

April 11, 1956.

I think he knows.


The rushed-looking written letters looked weird to me. I flipped the next page only to find it blank. I flipped to more pages but the rest of the book was also spotless. I raised my eyebrows in surprise. Where did the rest of the story go? I was so disappointed with the book ending that way that I decided to hide where I cannot see it. I stood and went to the chest meaning to place the book in there. However, as soon as I opened the chest, a force pulled me inside and suddenly, I was falling down a deep dark tunnel. I tried to scream for help but it was futile, none could here me. Then, I landed with a thud, knocking my breath out of me.

The Wall

I lifted my eyes only to see that I was still in the master’s bedroom, only this time, I was not alone. a man in his thirties stood tall by the door frame while a woman kneels at the floor looking flustered. She had the black book as if she had just written something in it clutched in her hands.


“Dear,” she stammered. “I did not know you would be back so earlyỊ” She gave a nervous laugh that fooled no one. She was hiding something and the husband knows it.


“I though I heard the closet shut. Sure it is your maid that is in there.” Said the man, though not sounding very convinced. He sounded like he was convincing himself.


Just in time, the maid walked in shattering the illusion that it was her in the closet, which by the way, appeared to be the thing covered by the odd brick wall on the right wall.

The Wall


The man stepped forward and the lady stood, fixing her dress as she did and faced her husband. The man reached for the cross pendant of the lady and asked,


“I have never seen this piece before. Where did you get it?”


“A Spanish merchant sold it to me when the Spanish troops arrived.” she answered.


“Which merchant, name him.” Demanded the husband.


“Delgado.” she replied.

The Wall


“There is no one thereỊ” she cried.


“Do you swear?” asked the husband coldly as he turned to her.


“YesỊ Yes, I swear itỊ” she swore, tears welling in her eyes.


“Swear it on your cross.”


“I swear it on my cross.” she whispered as she held the pendant.


“I believe you.”

The husband then ordered his men to cover the closet door with bricks, one by one, a wall formed. Before they could fully close the opening, as the husband turned around to receive the news that there was no merchant named Delgado in their city records, a hand dropped on the last brick laid on the forming wall.

The Wall

The lady screamed and the hand went away just in time for the husband to turn around and see nothing. He ignored her shout and paid the informant handsomely. For the next three months, the husband stayed in the room with his slowly going insane wife. From time to time, she would beg him to take down the wall, but every time, he would remind her that she swore there was no one in there.


Out of nowhere, the wooden chest spat me out and I was back in the room once more, now in the present. With eyes wide, I tried to process what just happened, the things I just witnessed. I still had the book in my hands and there was a loose page protruding from it. I took it and opened the folded paper to find a sleekly written letter.

The Wall

April 10, 1956


From the moment I saw you, I knew you were the one. I just knew to myself that I must have you. And so have you, I did. I did it even though I knew it was wrong and against God. But Marie, I am in love with you. With all my being, I love you. I thank you for the brief time we were together. But if you are reading this letter, then it means I am already gone. But know, that I will come back for you--always, mi amore.


Alejandro


I


I looked at the brick wall on the right side of the room and an unparalleled shiver ran through me.


“MariaỊ”


I heard a car pull over down the driveway and someone calling my name, probably my husband.


Then, a knock came from the other side of the brick wall. I looked over to it shocked and found, nailed into the frame of the picture of The last supper, the Gothic necklace.

The Mysterious Mansion


THE MYSTERIOUS MaNSION BY HONORE dE Balzac This is one of the best known of Balzac's short stories, and may be said to rank among the half-dozen best of all. It is one of his "Studies of Women," its French title is "la Grande Breteche," it forms part of the second volume in the series entitled "Scenes from Private life," and was first published in 1830.

The Mysterious Mansion


about a hundred yards from the town of vendôme, on the borders of the loire, there is an old gray house, surmounted by very high gables, and so completely isolated that neither tanyard nor shabby hostelry, such as you may find at the entrance to all small towns, exists in its immediate neighborhood. In front of this building, overlooking the river, is a garden, where the once well- trimmed box borders that used to define the walks now grow wild as they list. several willows that spring from the loire have grown as rapidly as the hedge that encloses it, and half conceal the house. The rich vegetation of those weeds that we call foul adorns the sloping shore. Fruit trees, neglected for the last ten years, no longer yield their harvest, and their shoots form coppices.

The Mysterious Mansion


The wall-fruit grows like hedges against the walls. Paths once graveled are overgrown with moss, but, to tell the truth, there is no trace of a path. From the height of the hill, to which cling the ruins of the old castle of the Dukes of vendôme, the only spot whence the eye can plunge into this enclosure, it strikes you that, at a time not easy to determine, this plot of land was the delight of a country gentleman, who cultivated roses and tulips and horticulture in general, and who was besides a lover of fine fruit. An arbor is still visible, or rather the débris of an arbor, where there is a table that time has not quite destroyed. The aspect of this garden of bygone days suggests the negative joys of peaceful, provincial life, as one might reconstruct the life of a worthy tradesman by reading the epitaph on his tombstone. As if to complete the sweetness and sadness of the ideas that possess one's soul, one of the walls displays a sun-dial decorated with the following commonplace Christian inscription: "Ultimam cogitaỊ"

The Mysterious Mansion


The roof of this house is horribly dilapidated, the shutters are always closed, the balconies are covered with swallows' nests, the doors are perpetually shut, weeds have drawn green lines in the cracks of the flights of steps, the locks and bolts are rusty. Sun, moon, winter, summer, and snow have worn the paneling, warped the boards, gnawed the paint. The lugubrious silence which reigns there is only broken by birds, cats, martins, rats and mice, free to course to and fro, to fight and to eat each other. everywhere an invisible hand has graven the word mystery. Should your curiosity lead you to glance at this house from the side that points to the road, you would perceive a great door which the children of the place have riddled with holes. I afterward heard that this door had been closed for the last ten years.

The Mysterious Mansion


Through the holes broken by the boys you would have observed the perfect harmony that existed between the façades of both garden and courtyard. In both the same disorder prevails. Tufts of weed encircle the paving-stones. enormous cracks furrow the walls, round whose blackened crests twine the thousand garlands of the pellitory. The steps are out of joint, the wire of the bell is rusted, the spouts are cracked. What fire from heaven has fallen here? What tribunal has decreed that salt should be strewn on this dwelling? Has God been blasphemed, has France been here betrayed? These are the questions we ask ourselves, but get no answer from the crawling things that haunt the place. The empty and deserted house is a gigantic enigma, of which the key is lost. In bygone times it was a small fief, and bears the name of the Grande Bretêche.
